Drilling is a complex destructive action that induces vibrations due to the rock-bit
interaction, which affects the overall drilling efficiency and wellbore quality. Previous
work has been conducted to predict the rate of penetration (ROP) and drilling
efficiency. However, the present study considers two additional datasets: in-cutter force
sensing data and vibrations. An artificial neural network (ANN) model utilizes the incutter
sensing data and the scaled drilling rig sensors to predict the rock strength and
rate of penetration. The model employs the acquired data, derived variables, and
mechanical properties of the rock samples to conduct the prediction. A scoring system
is used to evaluate the drilling efficiency by coupling the mechanical specific energy
and vibration modes. The reliability of the framework is demonstrated by testing the
validity of the ANN model on samples with various mechanical properties. Physicsbased
restrictions are applied for vibration, weight on bit, and torque to ensure the ML
model output falls within the working ranges of the scaled drilling rig. A sensitivity
analysis is conducted to optimize the ANN’s structure and determine the impact of
each drilling parameter on the ANN’s performance. Furthermore, it is demonstrated
that the ANN can produce accurate predictions for numerous rock samples.
